":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Nicholas Posyer was born in 1530, in Brasted, Kent, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Anne Miller. He died in 1575, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1530–1575":"1530–1575","1531–1575":"1531–1575","1542–Female":"1542–Surnud","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","Brasted, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Brasted, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1530–1575":"1530–1575","1531–1575":"1531–1575","1542–Female":"1542–Kuollut","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","Brasted, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Brasted, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1530–1575":"1530–1575","1531–1575":"1531–1575","1542–Female":"1542–Décédée","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1531":"1531","1530":"1530","Brasted, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Brasted, K